% 2. CHAPTER 2: LITERATURE REVIEW
% =======================================================
\section{Chapter 2: Literature Review}
\label{sec:literature_review}

\subsection{Introduction}
\label{subsec:lit_intro}
The exponential growth of digital reliance in academic institutions has fundamentally transformed university governance, but it has simultaneously introduced complex cyber-physical and information security vulnerabilities[cite: 9, 11]. This chapter reviews the theoretical and empirical foundations of information security risk management (ISRM) and data recovery frameworks within higher education[cite: 5, 6, 7]. Specifically, it synthesizes global risk assessment standards, critically evaluates the asset-centric OCTAVE Allegro methodology, reviews proactive disaster recovery and backup paradigms, and examines the specific challenges faced by resource-limited public universities[cite: 2, 3, 5, 8, 11]. Ultimately, this comprehensive review establishes the definitive theoretical framework for integrating risk assessment with operational continuity mechanisms[cite: 7, 8].

\subsection{Information Security Risk Management (ISRM) Frameworks}
\label{subsec:isrm_frameworks}
Scholarly literature emphasizes that establishing a robust protection profile requires systematic risk identification, analysis, and treatment protocols[cite: 6]. Academic and corporate organizations frequently leverage standardized guidelines to manage digital vulnerabilities[cite: 6].
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{ISO/IEC 27005 Standard:} This framework provides a phased approach for conducting comprehensive risk assessments, detailing precise stages to discover system assets, determine threat probabilities, and estimate potential baseline impact levels[cite: 6]. It helps organizations achieve a clearer view of assets to diminish the downstream impact of security incidents[cite: 6].
\item \textbf{NIST SP 800-30 Guide:} Developed as a benchmark for conducting risk assessments, this guide offers practical strategies to identify critical information parameters and counter prevailing cyber threats[cite: 6]. It focuses heavily on mapping systemic vulnerabilities against evolving threat vectors to reduce operational exposure[cite: 6].
\end{itemize}
While these traditional standards are highly effective, contemporary research indicates they often require substantial administrative overhead, extensive documentation, and costly consulting investments[cite: 11]. Consequently, resource-limited universities operating under tight budgets struggle to execute these frameworks successfully, driving the need for more practical, streamlined alternatives[cite: 11].

\subsection{The OCTAVE Allegro Methodology}
\label{subsec:octave_allegro_review}
The Operationally Critical Threat, Asset, and Vulnerability Evaluation (OCTAVE) technique, originally developed by the Software Engineering Institute (SEI) at Carnegie Mellon University, was designed to provide organizations with deep insights into their key assets and prevailing threats[cite: 2, 3]. 
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Asset-Centric Paradigm Shift:} Empirical research demonstrates that the core effectiveness of the OCTAVE Allegro variant lies in its explicit focus on the information assets themselves rather than the broader hardware, computers, or network technologies[cite: 2, 3]. This paradigm shift targets the conceptual and logical strongholds where sensitive data actually resides[cite: 2, 3].
\item \textbf{Structured Prioritization:} OCTAVE Allegro is highly structured, allowing practitioners to efficiently prioritize critical assets, evaluate institutional weaknesses, and analyze potential threat profiles without exhausting operational resources[cite: 2, 3].
\item \textbf{Practical Suitability for Resource-Limited Settings:} Because it simplifies risk calculation into clear operational steps, recent literature highlights OCTAVE Allegro as an ideal tool for organizations facing budget boundaries[cite: 5]. It prevents IT departments from spreading their limited personnel too thin by ensuring focus is directed entirely toward high-risk assets[cite: 5].
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Information Security Challenges in Higher Education}
\label{subsec:university_security_challenges}
Higher education institutions represent unique, highly complex computing environments[cite: 9]. Literature identifies several systemic factors that escalate academic cyber risks:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Complex Network Environments:} Modern universities manage distributed, open-access networks serving a vast multitude of concurrent users—including students, researchers, faculty, and administrative staff—which inherently increases the probability of internal leaks or external intrusions[cite: 9].
\item \textbf{Critical Asset Vulnerabilities:} Centralized infrastructures host highly sensitive student records, online registration portals, human resource records, grading databases, and financial systems[cite: 11]. PARALYZING any of these vital components immediately disrupts academic continuity, impacts transcript verification, and damages institutional trust[cite: 11].
\item \textbf{The Underfunded Public Sector Gap:} In developing or low-resource settings, public universities frequently skip necessary defensive deployments, operate outdated software full of security holes, and lack formal threat mitigation or enterprise-level business continuity plans[cite: 11].
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Data Recovery and Disaster Continuity Paradigms}
\label{subsec:recovery_paradigms}
Scholarly literature heavily validates that strong prevention frameworks are fundamentally incomplete without comprehensive recovery plans to handle the aftermath of a security breach or technical failure[cite: 8]. Maintaining business functionality during unexpected system crashes requires the strategic implementation of practical data resilience concepts:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{The 3-2-1 Backup Rule:} A globally recognized data preservation baseline specifying that an organization must maintain three (3) total copies of data, stored across two (2) distinct types of storage media, with at least one (1) copy securely maintained at an off-site or cloud-based location[cite: 5, 8]. This strategy minimizes the threat of localized physical damage from fires, floods, or hardware thefts[cite: 5, 11].
\item \textbf{Database Replication:} This technique maintains an identical, live copy of the active database instance[cite: 5, 8]. If the primary database system suffers a hardware failure, ransomware attack, or severe corruption, the replicated backup can immediately take over operations, preventing catastrophic data loss and minimizing operational downtime[cite: 5, 8].
\item \textbf{Disaster Recovery Planning (DRP):} A structured, step-by-step framework designed to restore operational capabilities within tight time constraints (e.g., target recovery window of four hours or less) following an incident[cite: 8]. A well-defined DRP maps recovery priorities, coordinates backup restoration, and establishes a systematic response to eliminate chaotic administrative downtime[cite: 8, 11].
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Synthesis and Identification of the Research Gap}
\label{subsec:research_gap}
A critical synthesis of the existing literature reveals a profound structural dichotomy in contemporary information security research[cite: 5, 8, 11]. On one hand, extensive frameworks exist for identifying and analyzing cybersecurity risks using methodologies like ISO 27005, NIST, and OCTAVE Allegro[cite: 2, 3, 6]. On the other hand, data resilience and disaster recovery strategies are heavily explored as technical, standalone engineering implementations[cite: 5, 8]. 

Crucially, there is an absolute scarcity of research that attempts to directly tie and integrate asset-centric risk analysis with operational data recovery models specifically designed for public higher education institutions operating within low-budget, low-tech environments[cite: 11]. Most existing integrated models assume the availability of deep corporate financial pockets, continuous luxury hardware funding, and advanced security configurations[cite: 11]. This research bridges this definitive gap by constructing a consolidated framework that leverages the resource-friendly evaluation steps of OCTAVE Allegro and merges them directly with low-cost, automated 3-2-1 backup schedules and disaster recovery protocols[cite: 2, 3, 5, 8, 11]. This approach ensures that a university's limited financial resources are spent precisely on securing its most vulnerable, high-impact instructional assets[cite: 11].


