\section{Chapter 3: Research Methodology}
\label{sec:methodology}

\subsection{Introduction}
\label{subsec:method_intro}
This chapter delineates the empirical research methodology and design deployed to assess information security risks and implement a data recovery framework within a resource-limited academic environment[cite: 11]. To establish a practical and context-specific investigation, this study adopts a single-site case study approach focused on Sana'a University[cite: 11]. The primary methodological objective is to structurally integrate the asset-centric OCTAVE Allegro risk evaluation framework with concrete, low-cost data recovery and disaster readiness mechanisms[cite: 2, 3, 11]. The subsequent sections detail the conceptual framework, population parameters, data collection protocols, and data analysis plans that govern this research workflow[cite: 7, 11].

\subsection{Conceptual Framework and Operationalization of Variables}
\label{subsec:conceptual_framework}
The conceptual framework of this study is systematically structured around the core phases of the OCTAVE Allegro methodology, customized to accommodate the operational realities of underfunded higher education institutions[cite: 2, 3, 5, 11]. The research workflow follows a sequential, five-stage logical process: (1) Asset Identification, (2) Threat Identification, (3) Risk Analysis, (4) Risk Classification, and (5) Solution Application[cite: 11].

To evaluate the security ecosystem, the core variables and risk components are operationalized as follows:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Information Assets ($A$):} The critical digital components sustaining university administration and education, operationalized via their Description and Importance Level (e.g., High or Very High)[cite: 11].
\item \textbf{Threat Vectors ($T$):} Potential disruptive incidents categorized into cybersecurity attacks (e.g., ransomware, unauthorized access), technical failures (e.g., server crashes), human errors (e.g., accidental data deletion), and environmental operational threats (e.g., power or network disruptions)[cite: 11].
\item \textbf{Probability of Occurrence ($P$):} The estimated likelihood of a threat vector exploiting a vulnerability, qualitatively scaled as Low, Medium, or High[cite: 11].
\item \textbf{Operational Impact ($I$):} The severity of logical or operational disruption to academic and administrative continuity if an incident occurs, scaled as Medium or High[cite: 11].
\item \textbf{Calculated Risk Level ($R$):} The final priority index derived mathematically by cross-referencing probability and impact ($R = P \times I$), classified into discrete priority bands: Low, Medium, High, or Very High[cite: 6, 11].
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Target Population, Sampling, and Institutional Context}
\label{subsec:population_sampling}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Target Institutional Setting:} The empirical boundary of this case study is explicitly confined to Sana'a University, Yemen[cite: 11]. This institution represents a critical baseline model for public higher education facilities suffering from severe budget limitations, inadequate technical resources, unstable power configurations, and the absence of enterprise security architectures[cite: 11].
\item \textbf{Target Population and Informants:} The target population for data collection comprises key technical stakeholders, IT administrators, and system engineers responsible for managing the university's centralized network, application servers, and institutional databases[cite: 11]. 
\item \textbf{Sampling Approach and Bias Controls:} Purposive sampling was used to select participants who possess direct operational access and administrative oversight of the primary digital assets[cite: 11]. To mitigate self-reporting bias or gaps in information sharing, qualitative input from administrative interviews was cross-checked against objective technical evidence extracted directly from historic system logs and operational data registries[cite: 11].
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Data Collection Instruments}
\label{subsec:data_instruments}
To capture both qualitative and quantitative risk parameters, three primary data collection instruments were utilized in this study[cite: 11]:
\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Semi-Structured IT Interviews:} Qualitative interview protocols were designed and conducted with university IT administrators[cite: 11]. These sessions focused on mapping daily operational tasks, examining current backup habits, exploring historic system crashes, and evaluating user training gaps regarding campus cybersecurity[cite: 11].
\item \textbf{System Log and Operational Data Reviews:} An empirical examination of server logs and historical operational data was carried out to identify past patterns of system slowdowns, hardware errors, unexpected power outages, and unauthorized access attempts[cite: 11].
\item \textbf{OCTAVE Allegro Risk Assessment Matrices:} Standardized risk evaluation tables based on the OCTAVE Allegro methodology were deployed to systematically log assets, descriptions, perceived threats, probability levels, and operational impacts[cite: 2, 3, 11].
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Data Analysis Plan and Integrated Mitigation Framework}
\label{subsec:analysis_plan}
The data analysis plan applies a mixed qualitative and quantitative approach to transform raw operational data into an actionable security framework[cite: 11]. The analytical pipeline executes the following sequential steps based on the OCTAVE Allegro steps[cite: 11]:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Phase 1: Critical Asset Mapping:} Notes from administrative interviews and system architectures are synthesized to produce a definitive catalog of core information assets, grading their importance based on their role in sustaining student registration and grading operations[cite: 11].
\item \textbf{Phase 2: Threat and Vulnerability Matrix Analysis:} Specific cybersecurity, operational, and human threats are mapped directly against individual assets[cite: 11]. Using a probability-impact matrix, each threat configuration is evaluated to establish a clear risk prioritization hierarchy, ensuring that limited university funds are targeted toward high-impact threats[cite: 6, 11].
\item \textbf{Phase 3: Integration of the Data Recovery Solution:} High-priority risks are directly addressed by building a practical data protection framework[cite: 11]. This plan integrates a periodic backup schedule (combining weekly full backups with daily incremental updates) and executes the 3-2-1 backup strategy to secure data offsite against physical disasters or localized hardware theft[cite: 5, 8, 11].
\item \textbf{Phase 4: Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP) Execution Modeling:} A procedural blueprint is designed to coordinate rapid system restoration after a crash, establishing priority recovery workflows for critical elements (such as the Student Database) with an operational target recovery time of four hours or less[cite: 8, 11].
\end{itemize}


