\section{Chapter 4: Results and Analysis}
\label{sec:results}

\subsection{Introduction}
\label{subsec:results_intro}
This chapter presents the empirical findings and analytical results derived from applying the asset-centric OCTAVE Allegro framework and the integrated data recovery architecture at Sana'a University[cite: 11]. The data gathered through semi-structured interviews and historical system log reviews are systematically analyzed to answer each of the primary and sub-research questions formulated in Chapter 1[cite: 11]. The results are organized into five sequential sections following the study's procedural workflow: asset identification, threat and vulnerability mapping, risk evaluation via the probability-impact matrix, the design of the 3-2-1 backup strategy, and the execution model of the Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP)[cite: 5, 8, 11].

\subsection{Asset Identification and Categorization (Step 1)}
\label{subsec:results_step1}
The initial phase of the field analysis focused on mapping and evaluating the digital assets that support the academic and administrative infrastructure of Sana'a University[cite: 11]. Based on empirical system data and qualitative IT staff logs, two primary systems were identified as the absolute operational strongholds of the university[cite: 11]. Table~\ref{tab:assets_identification} categorizes these critical information assets alongside their technical descriptions and institutional importance levels[cite: 11].

\begin{table}[htbp]
\caption{Information Asset Identification and Categorization}
\label{tab:assets_identification}
\centering
\begin{tabular}{l p{7cm} l}
\toprule
\textbf{Asset Name} & \textbf{Technical Description and Operational Role} & \textbf{Importance Level} \\
\midrule
Student Database & Central repository storing sensitive historical academic records, grades, transcript sheets, and active registration profiles[cite: 11]. & Very High[cite: 11] \\
\addlinespace
Student Information System & Primary web platform governing student admission, course enrollment, and administrative workflows[cite: 11]. & High[cite: 11] \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The findings demonstrate that any compromise to the Student Database instantly paralyses core institutional functions, establishing it as the most critical asset requiring advanced structural resilience[cite: 11].

\subsection{Threat Identification and Risk Assessment (Steps 2 \& 3)}
\label{subsec:results_steps2_3}
Following asset identification, potential threat vectors were analyzed by evaluating historical system logs, power failure frequencies, and security event histories at the university[cite: 11]. The discovered vulnerabilities are classified into four main categories: cybersecurity attacks, human errors, technical/hardware failures, and environmental operational threats[cite: 11]. Table~\ref{tab:threat_mapping} provides a detailed map of these threat vectors, their descriptions, and their underlying operational context[cite: 11].

\begin{table}[htbp]
\caption{Threat Identification and Vulnerability Mapping}
\label{tab:threat_mapping}
\centering
\begin{tabular}{l p{9cm}}
\toprule
\textbf{Threat Category} & \textbf{Specific Threat Vector and Operational Context} \\
\midrule
Cybersecurity Attacks & Ransomware deployment, unauthorized database access, and malicious credential exploitation[cite: 11]. \\
\addlinespace
Human Errors & Accidental deletion of data tables by system administrators or unauthorized modifications due to user training gaps[cite: 11]. \\
\addlinespace
Technical/Hardware Failures & Primary server crashes, hard drive damage, main storage corruption, and database application errors[cite: 11]. \\
\addlinespace
Environmental Threats & Frequent regional power interruptions and erratic network bandwidth disrupting real-time operations[cite: 11]. \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Risk Evaluation and Classification Matrix (Step 4)}
\label{subsec:results_step4}
To prioritize mitigation efforts under severe financial and resource limitations, a qualitative-quantitative risk assessment matrix was applied[cite: 6, 11]. Risk levels ($R$) are calculated by multiplying the Probability of Occurrence ($P$) by the Operational Impact ($I$)[cite: 6, 11]. Table~\ref{tab:risk_matrix} presents the calculated risk levels for each identified asset-threat configuration[cite: 11].

\begin{table}[htbp]
\caption{OCTAVE Allegro Risk Evaluation and Classification Matrix}
\label{tab:risk_matrix}
\centering
\begin{tabular}{l p{5cm} c c c}
\toprule
\textbf{Target Asset} & \textbf{Threat Vector} & \textbf{Probability ($P$)} & \textbf{Impact ($I$)} & \textbf{Calculated Risk Level ($R$)} \\
\midrule
Student Database & Ransomware Attacks & High & High & \textbf{Very High}[cite: 11] \\
Student Database & Accidental Deletion (Human Error) & Medium & High & \textbf{High}[cite: 11] \\
Student Database & Server Crash (Hardware Failure) & High & High & \textbf{Very High}[cite: 11] \\
\addlinespace
Information System & Unauthorized Access & High & Medium & \textbf{High}[cite: 11] \\
Information System & Power Outages \& Network Instability & High & Medium & \textbf{High}[cite: 11] \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

The matrix clearly shows that ransomware attacks and hardware server crashes targeting the Student Database present the highest operational risk to Sana'a University, requiring an immediate, integrated data recovery framework[cite: 11].

\subsection{The Data Recovery Solution and 3-2-1 Backup Strategy (Step 5)}
\label{subsec:results_step5_backup}
To address the very high risks identified without requiring expensive commercial licenses, a low-cost, automated backup schedule was designed and implemented[cite: 5, 11]. This mechanism combines a weekly full backup with daily incremental updates to capture ongoing changes while conserving limited storage space and network bandwidth[cite: 11]. 

This schedule is managed using the structured 3-2-1 backup strategy to eliminate single points of failure[cite: 5, 11]. The technical architecture is structured as follows:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{3 Total Copies of Data:} Includes the primary operational database production instance, one main local backup, and one offsite/cloud copy[cite: 5, 11].
\item \textbf{2 Different Physical Media Types:} The first copy is kept on local server hard disks (HDD/SSD), and the second copy is stored on a separate, detached External Hard Drive to protect against localized ransomware propagation[cite: 5, 11].
\item \textbf{1 Off-site Cloud Location:} Secure encrypted backups are uploaded to a remote cloud repository (e.g., Secure Google Drive/Cloud Storage) to safeguard university records against physical localized disasters, fires, or hardware theft on campus[cite: 5, 11].
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP) Execution and Performance Evaluation}
\label{subsec:results_drp}
To ensure administrative and academic continuity during a major system crash, a clear Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP) was formulated[cite: 8, 11]. The plan defines structured procedures to guide IT staff during restoration, replacing chaotic emergency responses with coordinated, step-by-step technical actions[cite: 8, 11]. Table~\ref{tab:drp_phases} outlines the phases, specific activities, and operational performance targets of the DRP[cite: 8, 11].

\begin{table}[htbp]
\caption{Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP) Phases and Performance Targets}
\label{tab:drp_phases}
\centering
\begin{tabular}{c l p{7cm} l}
\toprule
\textbf{Phase} & \textbf{DRP Stage} & \textbf{Action Steps and Execution Protocols} & \textbf{Performance Target} \\
\midrule
1 & Detection \& Isolation & Identify server crashes or ransomware entry, cut off network connections, and protect remaining storage systems[cite: 11]. & Within 30 Minutes[cite: 11] \\
\addlinespace
2 & System Rebuilding & Clear corrupted drives, reinstall base server operating systems, and verify configuration security[cite: 11]. & Within 2 Hours[cite: 11] \\
\addlinespace
3 & Data Restoration & Retrieve the latest uncorrupted data copy via the 3-2-1 system and restore the primary SQL database tables[cite: 5, 11]. & Within 1 Hour[cite: 11] \\
\addlinespace
4 & Verification \& Launch & Validate data integrity, check user login functionalities, and re-establish live student registration services[cite: 11]. & Within 30 Minutes[cite: 11] \\
\midrule
\multicolumn{3}{l}{\textbf{Total Target Recovery Time Objective (RTO):}} & \textbf{Less than 4 Hours}[cite: 11] \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

By executing this integrated model, the target Recovery Time Objective (RTO) is brought down to under four hours[cite: 11]. This demonstrates that resource-limited academic institutions can successfully achieve high operational resilience by combining the asset-centric focus of OCTAVE Allegro with practical, low-cost data recovery workflows[cite: 2, 3, 5, 11].

\newpage
% =======================================================
% 5. CHAPTER 5: DISCUSSION, CONCLUSIONS, AND RECOMMENDATIONS
% =======================================================
\section{Chapter 5: Discussion, Conclusions, and Recommendations}
\label{sec:discussion}

\subsection{Introduction}
\label{subsec:discussion_intro}
This final chapter provides a comprehensive synthesis of the empirical findings detailed in Chapter 4, interpreting them within the broader context of existing information security and data resilience literature[cite: 5, 8, 11]. As higher education institutions navigate escalating digital vulnerabilities, analyzing the operational intersection of risk management and low-cost recovery solutions becomes critical[cite: 9, 11]. The subsequent sections discuss the research findings, outline practical and policy-level implications for institutional stakeholders, present definitive study conclusions, and suggest strategic directions for future research[cite: 7, 11].

\subsection{Discussion of Empirical Findings}
\label{subsec:discussion_findings}
The application of the asset-centric OCTAVE Allegro framework at Sana'a University successfully filled a critical operational void by mapping high-priority vulnerabilities directly to core systems, specifically the Student Database and the Student Information System[cite: 2, 3, 11]. Traditional information security literature frequently prioritizes extensive hardware security controls and enterprise-level firewall architectures[cite: 6]. However, this study aligns with recent scholarly assertions that focusing on the information asset itself rather than the broader network infrastructure provides a significantly more efficient defense strategy for institutions with constrained budgets[cite: 2, 3, 11]. 

Furthermore, the results of the risk evaluation matrix confirmed that critical database corruption from ransomware attacks or server crashes poses a very high risk to academic continuity[cite: 11]. In contrast to traditional paradigms that treat risk identification and disaster recovery as independent fields, the integrated framework designed in this research bridges this gap[cite: 5, 8, 11]. By directly connecting risk levels with an automated 3-2-1 backup schedule and a structured Disaster Recovery Plan (DRP), this study demonstrates that an optimized target Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of less than four hours is fully achievable under severe financial and resource constraints[cite: 5, 8, 11].

\subsection{Practical and Policy Implications}
\label{subsec:implications}
The findings of this research carry significant implications for various organizational stakeholders and policymakers within higher education[cite: 11]:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{For University Administrators and IT Practitioners:} The study provides an actionable, low-cost blueprint to optimize information security without requiring expensive enterprise software licenses[cite: 11]. Implementing the 3-2-1 backup strategy using affordable local media and secure cloud drives allows IT staff to maintain high data resilience with minimal expenditure[cite: 5, 11].
\item \textbf{For Institutional Policy Development:} University governance bodies must establish formal disaster recovery protocols and update internal security frameworks[cite: 8, 11]. Policies should mandate a clear separation of emergency roles and define priority recovery steps to eliminate administrative chaos during an active system crash[cite: 8, 11].
\item \textbf{For Academic Staff and User Awareness:} Because human error and accidental deletion were classified as high-risk factors, institutional security policies must integrate periodic training sessions for system users to decrease internal vulnerability vectors[cite: 11].
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Conclusions}
\label{subsec:conclusions}
This research has successfully demonstrated that severe financial and technical constraints do not prevent public universities from achieving strong operational resilience[cite: 11]. By applying the five-stage logical process derived from OCTAVE Allegro, the study systematically identified critical academic assets, assessed threat probabilities, and mapped operational impacts at Sana'a University[cite: 11]. 

The primary conclusion of this study is that integrating asset-centric risk assessment directly with structured data recovery plans optimizes incident response capabilities and secures vital student records against catastrophic loss[cite: 2, 3, 5, 11]. The proposed low-cost framework proves that combining automated incremental backup schedules, the 3-2-1 backup layout, and targeted DRP execution timelines can bring system downtime down to under four hours, offering a highly replicable security model for developing environments[cite: 5, 8, 11].

\subsection{Recommendations for Future Research}
\label{subsec:future_research}
While this study establishes a foundational model for resource-limited universities, several strategic areas require future scholarly investigation:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Framework Automation:} Future studies should explore the development of lightweight, open-source automation scripts to manage real-time replication and cloud syncing without increasing administrative overhead[cite: 5, 11].
\item \textbf{Multi-Site Validation:} Expanding the research design to include a multi-site comparative analysis across multiple public universities would test the generalizability of the proposed framework in diverse institutional environments[cite: 6, 11].
\item \textbf{Advanced Threat Modeling:} As threat vectors evolve, future research should integrate decentralized security mechanisms, such as immutable storage configurations, to enhance protection against advanced ransomware encryption techniques[cite: 11].
\end{itemize}


